<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="179" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[322,1719,350,917]" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">
This dark brown ant is widespread in the Pacific islands from Marquesas, Tahiti, 
<collectingCountry box="[468,587,723,767]" name="Samoa" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Samoa</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[621,689,723,767]" name="Fiji" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Fiji</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[722,839,723,767]" name="Tonga" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Tonga</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[873,1157,723,767]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, New Britain, Solomons and Papua. Now recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[840,944,776,818]" name="Guam" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Guam</collectingCountry>
for the first time. We found it widely distributed, and the most abundant of the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1203,1356,826,869]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1356,826,869]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Pheidole</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1420,1528,826,869]" name="Guam" pageId="4" pageNumber="179">Guam</collectingCountry>
. Determination by M. R. Smith.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
